body.plain: Carrie Marie Underwood (born March 10, 1983) is an American country music singer, songwriter, and actress. She rose to fame as the winner of the fourth season of American Idol in 2005. Underwood has since become a multi-platinum selling recording artist, a winner of six Grammy Awards, sixteen Billboard Music Awards, seven American Music Awards and ten Academy of Country Music Awards, among several others. As a songwriter, she has been nominated for a Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song. Underwood is also a two-time winner of the Academy of Country Music Entertainer of the Year award and the first woman to win such an award twice (2009/10). Underwood was inducted into and became a member of the Grand Ole Opry in 2008. She was also inducted into the Oklahoma Music Hall of Fame in 2009.

body.plain: “Before He Cheats” sees Underwood teaching an unfaithful lover a lesson. As the third single from 2005’s Some Hearts, the track became the first country song in history to sell over two million digital copies, and won two Grammy awards, for Best Female Country Vocal Performance and Best Country Song. Since its release, it has been certified five times platinum by the RIAA, selling five million copies.

description.plain:
This song follows Underwood’s journey of coming to terms with herself and her difference of appearance after an accident. She fell on the steps of her home and had to receive 40-50 stitches on her face.

In “Cry Pretty”, she exposes her vulnerability and insecurities and gives power to them, empowering and enabling others to feel comfortable doing the same. She tells listeners to join her in embracing their emotions even when they aren’t “pretty”. It is common for people in this society both men and women, to suppress their emotions because they feel they will be viewed as weak or ugly if seen crying or under turmoil. She sends a message to those fans about how unrealistic it is for them to expect to be able to maintain an attractive appearance when going through distress and to embrace how they look. This song promotes healthy expectations, body love, anti-shame and general acceptance.

annotatable.link_title: The Champion by Carrie Underwood (Ft. Ludacris)

body.plain:
On the 6th of January 2018, “Champion” was officially previewed during the NFL Wild Card game between the Atlanta Falcons and Los Angeles Rams.

Carrie Underwood’s Instagram page also posted a clip previewing the song:



The first collaboration between 7-times Grammy Winner/Country superstar Carrie Underwood and rapper Ludacris leaked two days before its official release which was set for Friday January 12th.

Underwood has not released a solo single since she dropped “Dirty Laundry” from her 2015 album Storyteller back in September 2016. Her most recent collaboration was “The Fighter”  duet released in February 2017 and featured on Keith Urban’s Grammy-nominated Ripcord album.

The song will also be the first new music Carrie releases since revealing facial injuries caused after falling outside her Nashville home back in November 2017. She also revealed that the accident was much more serious than originally thought, resulting in “between 40 and 50 stitches” to her face.

body.plain:
“Smoke Break” is the lead single from Carrie Underwood’s fifth studio album, Storyteller. The track, written with Hillary Lindsey and Chris DeStefano, premiered on August 20, 2015 at country radio and was digitally released on August 21.

Underwood announced “Smoke Break” and accompanying album Storyteller in a video posted to Facebook, in which she also described its meaning:

The song itself is … one of those story songs that I feel like everyone can relate to about how life is so hectic and it’s so nice if and when you actually get to kind of step away for a second. We all need that time to ourselves, to get to take a break.

According to USA Today, the track came to life while getting stuck working one of the other tracks on Storyteller:

We were writing and kept taking breaks to go outside because we were getting a little stuck on a song we were already working on. It was so beautiful outside, that we had a hard time focusing so we decided to write a song about taking breaks! “Smoke Break” seemed like a great title, so we ran with it!

body.plain:
When your car loses control on a snow-covered road, who do you turn to?

Released in 2005, the Brett James, Hillary Lindsey and Gordie Sampson penned “Jesus Take the Wheel” was a huge hit on both Country and Christian Billboard charts. Underwood took home Grammys for Best Country Song and Best Female Country Vocal, as well as the American Country Music Award for Single of the Year.

body.plain: This chilling, vengeful tale of a young girl with an abusive, alcoholic father is the title track of American Country singer Carrie Underwood’s fourth studio album. Speaking to a group of Nashville journalists, the singer discussed naming the record after this song: “The first time I heard the song, I knew I had to have it and it was like, ‘That’s the title!’ Hopefully everyone will be blown away by the album. I think it’s pretty special. Hopefully it’s not just the title track but the feeling people will get when they listen to it.”

body.plain:
“Church Bells” is the fourth single from Carrie Underwood’s fifth studio album Storyteller. It was released to country radio on April 3, 2016.

The song is about a young woman who marries a rich man, a marriage that comes somewhat violent and she ends up poisoning him “mysteriously” in order to free herself.

Carrie Underwood calls it “Fancy’s little sister”, referring to Reba McEntire’s 1991 single.

body.plain:
The fourth track from Storyteller finds Carrie singing a romantic ode to her lover. Apart from the obvious theme of love, there’s a definite theme of isolation. Clearly, Carrie wants this person all to herself.

Sam Hunt provides backup vocals throughout the track. He and Carrie performed a mashup of this song and his hit “Take Your Time” at the 2016 Grammys.

body.plain: “Just a Dream” is a song in which the listener is never quite sure about whether it’s reality or a dream. The song describes a young woman heading to the church to wed her fiance, but quickly spirals into a funeral. Whether the insistence that “this is just a dream” is literal or just wishful thinking is left up to the listener to decide.

body.plain:
“Two Black Cadillacs” is the third single taken from Carrie Underwood’s fourth studio album Blown Away.

“Two Black Cadillacs” tells the story of two women who, when they realise they are both dating the same guy, set aside their differences and decide to take care of things together.

Speaking of the track, Underwood stated:

It was so much fun to write and just be in that room … and we didn’t really know what to expect or where we were headed or what we would end up with.

She continued:

It’s just drama. It’s drama, and it’s dark, but it’s also, you have to listen to the whole thing. You’re sucked in, from the beginning, from the music, and it’s just, you know somethings gonna happen.

The six minute long music video for the track, directed by veteran video-maker Paul R. Brown, also received nomination for Video of the Year at the Academy of Country Music Awards.

description.plain: Carrie Marie Underwood (born March 10, 1983) is an American country music singer, songwriter, and actress. She rose to fame as the winner of the fourth season of American Idol in 2005. Underwood has since become a multi-platinum selling recording artist, a winner of six Grammy Awards, sixteen Billboard Music Awards, seven American Music Awards and ten Academy of Country Music Awards, among several others. As a songwriter, she has been nominated for a Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song. Underwood is also a two-time winner of the Academy of Country Music Entertainer of the Year award and the first woman to win such an award twice (2009/10). Underwood was inducted into and became a member of the Grand Ole Opry in 2008. She was also inducted into the Oklahoma Music Hall of Fame in 2009.
